# TypeScript Conventions

## Code Style
- Use semicolons at the end of statements
- Use double quotes for strings
- Use trailing commas in objects and arrays
- Use explicit return types for functions
- Use `const` for immutable variables, `let` for mutable ones

## MCP Tool Patterns
Each MCP tool should follow this structure:

```typescript
// schema.ts
import { z } from "zod";

export const ToolNameSchema = {
  param1: z.string().describe("Description of parameter"),
  param2: z.number().optional(),
};

// tool.ts
import { ToolNameSchema } from "./schema";
import { tool, text } from "../tool-utils";

export const handler = tool(ToolNameSchema, async (args) => {  if(/* there is an error*/) {
    throw new Error("Sample Error")
  }
  // Implementation
  return text("Sample response")
};
```

## Database Operations
- Always use `ObjectId` for MongoDB IDs: `new ObjectId(id)`
- Use typed collections from [packages/backend/src/db/collections/](mdc:packages/backend/src/db/collections/)
- Include proper error handling and logging
- Use console.log with context prefixes: `[tool-name] Message`

## Error Handling
- Wrap database operations in try-catch blocks
- Return structured error responses
- Log errors with context information
- Update document status on failure (e.g., marking_status: "failed")

## Environment Variables
- Use SST Resource pattern: `Resource.OpenAiApiKey.value`
- Define types in [sst-env.d.ts](mdc:sst-env.d.ts)
- Never hardcode sensitive values
description:
globs:
alwaysApply: false
